title: SafeIntOnOverflow in non-existent node Transpose_719

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
### Describe the issue

I am seeing the following exception for a model in production:
```
2023-01-22 13:09:51.094435070 [E:onnxruntime:, sequential_executor.cc:369 Execute] Non-zero status code returned while running Transpose node. Name:'Transpose_719' Status Message: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/common/safeint.h:17 static void SafeIntExceptionHandler<onnxruntime::OnnxRuntimeException>::SafeIntOnOverflow() Integer overflow

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "script.py", line 258, in main
    session.run(outputs, inputs, run_options=run_options)
  File "/path/to/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py", line 200, in run
    return self._sess.run(output_names, input_feed, run_options)
onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.RuntimeException: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 6 : RUNTIME_EXCEPTION : Non-zero status code returned while running Transpose node. Name:'Transpose_719' Status Message: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/common/safeint.h:17 static void SafeIntExceptionHandler<onnxruntime::OnnxRuntimeException>::SafeIntOnOverflow() Integer overflow
```

This is occurring in the decoder graph of a Transformer model, and seems (although I unfortunately can't prove it) to be correlated to very large inputs (batches that are pushing the limits of the NVIDIA T4 GPU's 16GiB of memory – a batch size of around 70 to 300 and up to 1500 tokens per segment). I was testing segments that caused OOMs, and this exception came up more often in the datasets with more OOMs, and far less often in the more normal datasets.

My reason for submitting this issue, and my main question is: Why is it reporting that this occurs in node `Transpose_719`? My model does not have 719 Transpose nodes – it doesn't have 719 nodes total! Occasionally, this exception also occurs for the nodes `Concat_718` and `Transpose_15`, neither of which exist in my model, either. 

Is there documentation on where the node names reported in this exception come from? I'm not sure how to debug this further without knowing where this integer overflow is occurring.

Edit: For the session used in these tests, I first loaded it into ORT with all optimizations enabled, then exported and used that optimized graph for everything mentioned above. The session is created with
`onnxruntime.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL` to ensure that the ONNX graph I can see/inspect in Netron is identical to the one being run.

### To reproduce

I unfortunately cannot share the ONNX graph producing this. I'd be very open to being told next steps for debugging this, and following them myself, so that I can find a shareable minimal example graph and set of inputs that triggers this.

title: Memory leak in C++ API with Core ML backend

labels.name: platform:mobile
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime mobile; typically submitted using template

body:
### Describe the issue

Using the C++ API with the CoreML backend we observed memory leaks, in particular each call to `Ort::Session::Run()` leaked a significant amount of memory.

We were able to fix the particular leak with following patch, but the problem does not only affect this one call.
```
--- a/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm
+++ b/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm
@@ -333,7 +333,9 @@ Status Execution::Predict(const std::unordered_map<std::string, OnnxTensorData>&
   ORT_RETURN_IF_NOT(model_loaded, "Execution::Predict requires Execution::LoadModel");
 
   if (HAS_VALID_BASE_OS_VERSION) {
-    return [execution_ predict:inputs outputs:outputs];
+    @autoreleasepool {
+        return [execution_ predict:inputs outputs:outputs];
+    }
   }
 
   return ORT_MAKE_STATUS(ONNXRUNTIME, FAIL, "Execution::LoadModel requires macos 10.15+ or ios 13+ ");
```

This code calls an Objective C method from Apple's Core ML API. These Objective C methods do not always fully release all of the temporary objects that they have created, they may only add them to the current autorelease pool, to be released when that pool is drained. However, the C++ code calling the `Ort` API has no idea of Objective C's autorelease pools, so none may exist or it may never be drained, and the objects are leaked.

Therefore the code in `onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml` which interfaces between C++ and Objective C would have to take care of creating and draining autorelease pools, but it currently doesn't.

One solution will be to sprinkle `@autoreleaepool` blocks around all calls to CoreML methods in the two Objective C++ files in `coreml/model`. I can certainly prepare a PR that does this, but maybe there is a more elegant solution. I do not normally write Objective C code, and someone here may feel ownership for the CoreML interface code.

(We are using 1.12.1, but I have not seen any relevant difference to the main branch.)

```py
    output_name = model.graph.output[0].name

    session = ort.InferenceSession(
        model.SerializeToString(),
        providers=providers,
    )

    x1 = np.random.randn(1, 2).astype(np.float32)
    x2 = np.random.randn(1, 2).astype(np.float32)

    inputs = session.get_inputs()

    # When x1 is not provided, the output should be `x2 + const` (const=1)
    ort_inputs = {inputs[0].name: None, inputs[1].name: x2}
    ort_outs = session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)[0]
    np.testing.assert_equal(ort_outs, x2 + 1)

    ort_outs = session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)[0]
    np.testing.assert_equal(ort_outs, x1 + x2)

    x2 = np.random.randn(1, 2).astype(np.float32)
    x3 = np.random.randn(1, 2).astype(np.float32)
    inputs = session.get_inputs()

    # When x3 is provided, output should always be `x3 + const` (const=2)
    ort_inputs = {inputs[0].name: x1, inputs[1].name: x2, inputs[2].name: x3}
    ort_outs = session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)[0]
    np.testing.assert_equal(ort_outs, x3 + 2)

    ort_inputs = {inputs[0].name: None, inputs[1].name: x2, inputs[2].name: x3}
    ort_outs = session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)[0]
    np.testing.assert_equal(ort_outs, x3 + 2)

    # and x1 is provided, the output should be `x1 + x2`
    ort_inputs = {inputs[0].name: x1, inputs[1].name: x2, inputs[2].name: None}
    ort_outs = session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)[0]
```

title: Do not create Barrier and triggerDownstream steps if the corresponding nodes are split by yield Op in training scenario
body:
### Description
Do not create Barrier and triggerDownstream steps during execution plan creation if the corresponding nodes are split by yield Op in training scenario. 



### Motivation and Context
In training scenario, forward and backward processes are running two different partial nodes of a graph. If there are two nodes each in one of the partial graph and separate in two streams, there are still triggerDownstream/barrier steps between them which work quite different from inference process as one of the steps will not be executed due to it is not in the correct range. To make it work, there is a hacky way to trigger the barrier step explicitly for training.
This PR is to do some check, and do not create Barrier and triggerDownstream steps if the corresponding nodes are split by yield Op in training scenario. So the hacky way is not needed.

### Describe the issue

Create some big inference sessions. (say >2GB).

This increases memory by 2GB on the GPU and also in the RAM by 2GB.

Call session.Dispose();

This clears the memory from the GPU but keeps memory on the RAM.

Thus 2GB of RAM is not being deleted.

Close the program. The RAM is finally freed.


**Why is this a problem?**
When working in an IDE such as Unity, there needs to be a way to free the RAM without closing the IDE. Each time you run the program without exiting the IDE, the RAM increases until memory error occurs.

What could be happening? Maybe it is loading the onnx file onto RAM but not freeing it after putting it on the GPU. Just a guess.


**Possible Reason**
This seems to happen mostly with big 2GB files. Which I noticed often have their weights in separate files. So perhaps the runtime is freeing memory from the main file but is not freeing the memory of the linked files such as weights.pb

Using C# onnx runtime latest developer build. 1.14 and also tried it on 1.15

title: Fix softmax block forward with small element size
body:
### Description
1. ALIGN_BYTES is set to 16 before because float4 is used for vectorization by default. This PR computes ALIGN_BYTES by vectorize size.
2. Fix wrong data access when using small elemant size (e.g., 1, 33). Small case may be used for SoftmaxTunableOp.
3. Fix the bug that data may be written first and then read in BlockReduce function on ROCm EP. There is a slightly performance improvement because all theads in warp-0 work.

BlockReduce method before this PR:
One block has N(warps_per_block) warps, one warp has M(WARP_SIZE) threads.
step1. All the threads in one block read data into shared memory.
step2. Reduce all data to the first warp. Only the first N threads of warp-0 are used. thread-0 computes data in warp-0 and writes the result into the location of data0, thread-1 computes data in warp-1 and writes the result into the location of data1.
         __syncwarp(mask) is necessary here to make sure thread-1,...N will delay writing data into warp-0 until thread-0 has finished reading data from warp-0.
step3. Thread-0 reduces all vaild data(only the first N data) in warp-0 and writes the results into the location of data0, then return data0.

Issue: ROCm doesn't support __syncwarp() now, we need another implementation to make sure read before write in warp-0.

BlockReduce function in this PR.
step2. Reduce all data to the first warp. Only the threads of warp-0 are used. Each thread in warp-0 read data from the same location of every warp and computes result. For example, thread-0 computes the first data of every warp and writes the result into the location of data0.
step3. Thread-0 reduces all data in warp-0 and writes the results into the location of data0, then return data0.

body:
### Describe the issue

Discovered by PyTorch exporter, the 1.14RC1 seems to exhibit side effects on graph output that was used as one of the inputs for "quantizeLinear" operator. The output should be `np.array(1.0)`, but instead becomes `None` in 1.14RC1.

The repro script and comparison between ORT 1.14RC1 and 1.13 can be found below.

### To reproduce

```python
import onnx
from onnx import numpy_helper
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime
import onnxscript
from onnxscript import opset17 as op

@onnxscript.script()

    y_scale = op.Constant(value_float=1.0)
    y_zero_point = op.Constant(

    )
    return op.QuantizeLinear(x, y_scale, y_zero_point), y_scale, y_zero_point

model: onnx.ModelProto = repro.to_model_proto()
onnx.save(model, "model.onnx")

session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("model.onnx")

print(session.run(None, {"x": x}))
```

title: [CUDA] Improve BeamSearch op's performance (GPT-2 use-case )
body:
### Description
1) Pre-allocate buffers for `present` and `past` states so that they can be used for every decoding run call (Pre-allocate a chunk for ALL layers based on `max_seq_length`)

2) Today, the way we pick the next iteration's input past states from the previous iteration's output present states for the chosen beams is by invoking `cudaMemcpyAsync()` in a nested loop (for each layer for each past/present count), This brings in a lot of cuda kernel launch overheads. We will replace all of these calls by one kernel that will pick the past states for the chosen beams for ALL layers into the present state buffer (hence step 1 is needed) and all the afore-mentioned kernel launch overheads are now eliminated.

### Motivation and Context
Tested this change on Ubuntu-T4 for batch size = 3, input_seq_length = 6, max_seq_length = 128, beam_width = 4, num_return_sequences = 1 and the total speed-up is about 21%. All the D2D copies and their kernel launches are eliminated as can be confirmed through profiling.

title: Changes to support standalone custom ops in a minimal build.
body:
### Description
<!-- Describe your changes. -->
Changes to support standalone custom ops in a minimal build. Also incorporates changes from #14492 (needed to test builds prior to that being checked in).

We first need to save the schema info from the operators used by the standalone op invoker in the ORT format model. Add mechanism for that.

Merge the kernel lookup logic so the same is used in full and minimal build. NOTE: the version matching is now consistent with all other kernel lookups, and the call to CreateOp MUST use the exact version for the operator. Previously matching wasn't as strict, but this can lead to the incorrect kernel being chosen. 

Add tests.

NOTE: There is currently no way to detect the ops/types/opsets used inside these custom ops as they don't exist until we create kernels, which is after model loading completes (which is the point the ORT format model is saved). Due to that they have to be manually added to the configuration used to do the reduced ops build. That shouldn't be too hard for the custom op author to add given the custom op implementation is specifying the op, opset and type constraints (i.e. they have the info and it's just a case of capturing/formatting it correctly).

title: Support external output tensors for DORT
body:
### Description
<!-- Describe your changes. -->
Support externally-managed output tensors (torch Tensors) for dort. 
Add `preallocate_output` option to OrtBackend to rely on externally-managed output tensors for dort.


### Motivation and Context
<!-- - Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. -->
DORT currently allocates and returns output ortvalues and convert them to torch Tensors. The conversion based on dlpack does not support torch Tensors for custom Aten backends, and it is not yet possible to transfer the ownership from ortvalue to external handle (torch Tensor). 

To avoid this issue, the PR change provides an option (`preallocate_output`) to allocate output tensors externally in pytorch, which creates torch Tensor for an Aten backend, and let dort take pointers from torch Tensors to construct output ortvalues instead of allocating them inside InferenceSession.

title: [Performance] Find out why the GPU memory allocated with `CUDAExecutionProvider` is much larger than the ONNX size

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
### Describe the issue

I have a model that is 4137 MB as a .onnx, exported from a PyTorch's `ScriptModule` through `torch.onnx.export`.

When loading the ONNX model through an InferenceSession using `CUDAExecutionProvider`, **18081 MB** of memory gets allocated on GPU.

When loading the `.pt` weights into a `ScriptModule` on GPU, PyTorch allocates only 5386 MB, which is more reasonable compared to the `.pt` size that is 4267 MB.

Hence, I am wondering how is memory allocation on GPU performed with `CUDAExecutionProvider`, and why it may be more than x4 the ONNX size. It could very well be that my ONNX is ill-formatted, so I'd like to find out where.

### To reproduce

Use this script to find out peak GPU memory allocation (MB):
```sh
a=0
while true; do 
b=$(nvidia-smi --query-gpu=memory.used --format=csv|grep -v memory|awk '{print $1}'| sed -n 2p) # gpu number 1
[ $b -gt $a ] && a=$b && c=$(bc -l <<<"1.048576*$a") && echo $c
sleep .5
done
```

Use this script to load the `ScriptModule`:
```python
import torch
import time

scripted_pipeline = torch.load("scripted_sd_cuda.pt")
scripted_pipeline = scripted_pipeline.to("cuda")
time.sleep(3)
```

Use this script to load the ONNX model:
```python
import onnxruntime as ort
import time

providers = ["CUDAExecutionProvider"]

session_options = ort.SessionOptions()
session_options.graph_optimization_level = (
    ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_BASIC
)

session = ort.InferenceSession("stable_diffusion_pipeline.onnx", providers=providers, sess_options=session_options)
time.sleep(3)
```

use:

title: Fix an issue that the Transpose Optimizer inserts more Transpose nodes
body:
Fix an issue that the Transpose Optimizer inserts more Transpose nodes which introduce more cost.

### Description
It happens to a QDQ model which has layout sensitive op GlobalAveragePool.
------------Transpose(nothing to do with channel last or channel first transformation)
-----Q----------Q
-----DQ--------DQ
------- \ ----------/
---------Concat
------------Q
------------DQ
--------- / ----- \\
-----MatMul--Slice

After Transpose Optimizer:
----Q------------
Transpose---Q
----DQ------DQ
----- \ ------ /
------Concat
-------- Q
------- DQ
------ /---- \\
Transpose -- Slice->Q->Transpose->DQ
-MatMul---------

1. It inserts more Transpose nodes around Concat. The existing Transpose node on right side of Concat input gets removed. It inserts a Transpose node on anther Concat input. It inserts Transpose nodes on Concat output and duplicate it at the consumer side. 
It inserts 2 more Transpose nodes comparing to the original model. It could introduce even more if Concat has more inputs without Transpose.
This pattern repeats more than 10 places in the model. It has big impact for the efficiency.
2. It moves Transpose to wrong places which breaks QDQ node group for MatMul.
    It moves Transpose to the place between DQ->MatMul which breaks the QDQ node group for MatMul.

Root cause:
Transpose Optimizer introduces more Transpose nodes to the graph.
1. Transpose Optimizer does it correctly before Layout Transformer applied. It calculate the cost to see whether it is worth to do some optimization for the Transpose nodes around the given node.
2. After Layout Transformer applied, more Transpose (NCHW->NHWC, NHWC->NCHW) nodes introduced. The problem is after Layout Transformer applied. Transpose Optimizer does 2nd round optimization without any cost evaluation.

Fix:
The 2nd round Transpose Optimizer should focus on the inserted new Transpose nodes which relate to channel first/last transformation.
This fix is limit the 2nd round to exclude Transpose which are nothing to do with channel first/last transformation. It unblocks the model we have.
It could still happen if the existing Transpose nodes on Concat input is relate to channel first/last transformation. It still requires further investigation and fix.

### Motivation and Context
1. As an optimizer, it shouldn't introduce more cost (inserting more Transpose nodes) to the model.
2. It should move Transpose node to correct place, shouldn't break existing QDQ node groups

labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
QAT performs training using all model parameters in floating point (in order to train these params).

We can work around the weights and activations by ensuring that they are always associated with `QDQ` pairs (so the input to the Q node is in float32) and subsequently converting these `QDQ` pairs to `FakeQuant` (in order to compute the gradient using `FakeQuantGrad`).

But biases are not associated with `QDQ` pairs since they are quantized in int32. In order for QAT to work, we need the biases to be in floating point format.

With this pull request, we address this by just removing the `DQ` that is associated with the biases and not quantize the bias at all. This does not negatively impact training.

title: Support building a QAT onnx model using onnxblock

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
After performing static quantization, the quant params are a part of the model initializers.

`onnxblock` treats model initializers as model parameters (for most scenarios) since it does not know how to (*smartly*) distinguish between model parameters and model initializers (consts or overridable initializers).

Quant params are not learnable (for now), so these parameters should not be used to build gradients. Moreover, we even avoid moving these parameters to graph inputs because these parameters are simply scalars (or 1d tensors).

This pull request adds support for doing the above in `onnxblock`.
